"step_by_step_thinking": "The question asks about a person on a fat-free carbohydrate-rich diet who continues to grow obese. This implies that the person is consuming high amounts of carbohydrates, which are broken down into glucose and absorbed by the bloodstream. Since the person is not consuming fats, we can rule out chylomicron (which carries dietary fats) and VLDL (which carries triglycerides from the liver). HDL is a high-density lipoprotein that carries cholesterol from peripheral tissues to the liver for excretion. LDL is low-density lipoprotein that carries cholesterol from the liver to peripheral tissues. Since the person is consuming high-carbohydrate diet, it's likely that their blood glucose levels are elevated, which would stimulate an increase in VLDL production and secretion from the liver.",
